Is it the shoes? Can't be. American women playing professional basketball do not have contracts with shoe manufacturers.

Is it to promote goodwill and global expansion of a burgeoning enterprise like the National Basketball Association? Not really. American women have no league at home to sell and must go to Europe and Japan to pursue their careers.

While marketing is unquestionably at or close to the bottom line of the N.B.A.'s pot-of-gold Summer Olympics pursuit next month, the veteran players who will make up the United States women's team are here to make a different kind of pitch.

"This is the only time we ever get recognized, during the Olympics," said Teresa Edwards, one of nine former Olympians among the 18 finalists named today for the team that Coach Theresa Grentz will take to Barcelona, Spain. "The men have everything." Experience Necessary